The article announces three nominations and appointments made by the United States government. Eliot Pedrosa of Florida is nominated to be the United States Alternate Executive Director of the Inter-American Development Bank. Pedrosa is a lawyer and currently works at Greenberg Traurig law firm. He is also the chairman of the Dean’s Advisory Council of the Green School of International and Public Affairs at Florida International University.

Charles E. Cook III of Maryland is nominated to be the Chief Financial Officer of the Department of Homeland Security. Cook has extensive experience in financial management and has served in the Federal Government’s Senior Executive Service for 20 years. He holds a bachelor's degree in business administration and accounting.

John L. Ryder of Tennessee is appointed as a Member of the Tennessee Valley Authority for a term of 5 years. Ryder replaces Richard C. Howorth, whose term has expired.